# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jsonlines
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] Data exchange is similar to data integration except that data may be restructured with possible loss of content.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] There may be no way to transform a particular collection based on exchange constraints.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] Conversely, there may be multiple ways to transform the data, in which case one option must be identified in order to achieve compatibility between source and target.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] There are two main types of data exchange: broadcast and peer-to-peer (a.k.a. unicast).
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] For broadcast, data is transmitted simultaneously to all consumers.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] Just as a conference call, all participants get the same information from the speaker at the same time.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] For peer-to-peer, data is sent to a single receiver, defined by a specific address.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] For example, a letter goes to just one mail box.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] In some domains, a multiple source and target schema (proprietary data formats) may exist.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] An exchange or interchange format is often developed for a single domain, and then necessary routines (mappings) are written to (indirectly) transform/translate each and every source schema to each and every target schema by using the interchange format as an intermediate step.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] That requires less work than writing and debugging the many routines that would be required to directly translate each source schema directly to each target schema.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] A data exchange (a.k.a. interchange) language defines a domain-independent way to represent data.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] These languages have evolved from being markup and display-oriented to support the encoding of metadata that describes the structural attributes of the information.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] Practice has shown that certain types of formal languages are better suited for this task than others, since their specification is driven by a formal process instead of particular software implementation.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] For example, XML is a markup language that was designed to enable the creation of dialects (the definition of domain-specific sublanguages).
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] However, it does not contain domain-specific dictionaries or fact types.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] Beneficial to a reliable data exchange is the availability of standard dictionaries-taxonomies and tools libraries such as parsers, schema validators, and transformation tools.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] The popularity of XML for data exchange on the World Wide Web has several reasons.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] First of all, it is closely related to the preexisting standards Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML) and Hypertext Markup Language (HTML), and as such a parser written to support these two languages can be easily extended to support XML as well.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] For example, XHTML has been defined as a format that is formal XML, but understood correctly by most (if not all) HTML parsers.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] YAML was designed to be human-readable and authored via a text editor with notion similar to reStructuredText and wiki syntax.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] YAML 1.2 also includes a shorthand notion that is compatible with JSON, and as such any JSON document is also valid YAML; this however does not hold the other way.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] REBOL was designed to be human-readable and authored via a text editor.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] It uses a simple free-form syntax with minimal punctuation and a rich set of data types (such as URL, email, date and time, tuple, string, tag) that respect common standards.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] It is designed to not need any additional meta-language, being designed in a metacircular fashion which is why the parse dialect used for definitions and transformations of REBOL dialects is also itself a dialect of REBOL.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] REBOL was used as a source of inspiration for JSON.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] The dictionary also includes standardized fact types.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] The terms and relation types together can be used to create and interpret expressions of facts, knowledge, requirements and other information.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] Gellish can be used in combination with SQL, RDF/XML, OWL and various other meta-languages.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] The Gellish standard is a combination of ISO 10303-221 (AP221) and ISO 15926.
[src:jsonlines/data-exchange] The following describes and compares popular data exchange languages.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] A **flat-file database** is a tabular flat file in which each record is semantically independent – can meaningfully be interpreted and manipulated independent of other records of the table.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] The term *flat* loosely refers to data that is record-based and sequential yet lacks more complicated aspects such as nesting, relationships and metadata (with the exception of column headers).
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] Relationships can be inferred from the data, but the format does not provide special accommodations for relationships.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] A flat-file database may be stored as plain text or binary (not character encoded).
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] When plain text, it is typically formatted as one record per line either as delimiter-separated or fixed-width.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] In delimiter-separated values files, the fields are separated by a character or string called the delimiter.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] Common variants are comma-separated values (CSV) where the delimiter is a comma, tab-separated values (TSV) where the delimiter is the tab character, space-separated values and vertical-bar-separated values (delimiter is `|`).
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] If the delimiter is allowed inside a field, there needs to be a way to distinguish delimiters characters or strings that are meant literally.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] For example, consider the sentence "If I have to, I'll do it myself.".
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] To encode it in CSV, there needs to be a way to prevent the comma from splitting the field.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] Several strategies to prevent delimiter collision exist.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] With fixed-width formats, each field has a fixed length with extra spaces added as needed.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] The fixed lengths can be predefined and known ahead of time (i.e. stated in the format's specification), or parsed from a header.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] With predefined lengths, fields are limited to a maximum length.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] The need for longer fields may appear sometime after the format is defined.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] Possible workarounds include abbreviating phrases, replacing values with links (e.g. a URI pointing to the value), and splitting a file into multiple files.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] With delimiter-separated formats, determining the field boundaries requires finding the delimiters, which incurs some computational overhead.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] This is not needed for fixed-width formats.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] However, fixed-width formats can lead to unnecessarily large file sizes if fields tend to be shorter than the lengths reserved for them.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] Delimiters can be used alongside a notation stating the length of each field.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] For example, `5apple|9pineapple` specifies the length (5 and 9) of each field.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] It has low overhead and trivially avoids delimiter collisions, but it is brittle when edited manually.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] In the 1980s, configurable flat-file database computer applications were popular on the IBM PC and the Macintosh.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] These programs were designed to make it easy for individuals to design and use their own databases, and were almost on par with word processors and spreadsheets in popularity.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] Examples of flat-file database software include early versions of FileMaker and the shareware PC-File and the popular dBase.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] Flat-file databases are common and ubiquitous because they are easy to write and edit, and suit myriad purposes in an uncomplicated way.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] Linear stores of NoSQL data, JSON data, primitive spreadsheets (perhaps comma-separated or tab-delimited), and text files can all be seen as flat-file databases because they lack integrated indexes, built-in references between data elements, and complex data types.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] Programs to manage collections of books or appointments and address books may use single-purpose flat-file databases, storing and retrieving information from flat-files unadorned with indexes or pointing systems.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] While a user can write a table of contents into a text file, the text file format itself does not include a concept of a table of contents.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] While a user may write "friends with Kathy" in the "Notes" section for John's contact information, this is interpreted by the user rather than a built-in feature of the database.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] In the context of Unix-like systems, the files `/etc/passwd` and `/etc/group` are flat-files databases.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] The following illustrates typical elements of a flat-file database.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] The information is arranged as a table – a series of rows and columns.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] The first row specifies the field names that are associated with the values of each row.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] The columns consist of an identifier (*id*), a person's name (*name*) and a team name (*team*).
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] Columns are separated by whitespace characters.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] This is also called indentation or "fixed-width" data formatting.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] Another common convention is to separate columns using one or more delimiter characters, such as a tab or comma.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] Each column may be restricted to a specific data type with restrictions usually enforced by convention.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] Each row or record meets the standard definition of a tuple under relational algebra.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] This example depicts a series of 3-tuples.
[src:jsonlines/flat-file-database] Since the formal operations possible with a text file are usually more limited than desired, the text in the above example would ordinarily represent an intermediary state of the data prior to being transferred into a database management system.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] JSON is a popular format for exchanging object data between systems.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] Frequently there's a need for a stream of objects to be sent over a single connection, such as a stock ticker or application log records.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] In these cases there's a need to identify where one JSON encoded object ends and the next begins.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] Line-delimited JSON works very well with traditional line-oriented tools.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] Concatenated JSON works with pretty-printed JSON but requires more effort and complexity to parse.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] It doesn't work well with traditional line-oriented tools.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] Concatenated JSON streaming is a superset of line-delimited JSON streaming.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] Length-prefixed JSON works with pretty-printed JSON.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] It doesn't work well with traditional line-oriented tools, but may offer performance advantages over line-delimited or concatenated streaming.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] Streaming makes use of the fact that the JSON format does not allow return and newline characters within primitive values (in strings those must be escaped as `\r` and `\n`, respectively) and that most JSON formatters default to not including any whitespace, including returns and newlines.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] These features allow the newline character or return and newline character sequence to be used as a delimiter.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] The use of a newline as a delimiter enables this format to work very well with traditional line-oriented Unix tools.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] which is very easy to sort by date, grep for usernames, actions, IP addresses, etc.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] Line-delimited JSON can be read by a parser that can handle concatenated JSON.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] Concatenated JSON that contains newlines *within* a JSON object can't be read by a line-delimited JSON parser.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] The terms "line-delimited JSON" and "newline-delimited JSON" are often used without clarifying if embedded newlines are supported.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] In the past the newline delimited JSON specification allowed comments to be embedded if the first two characters of a given line were "//".
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] This could not be used with standard JSON parsers if comments were included.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] Current version of the specification ("NDJSON - Newline delimited JSON ") no longer includes comments.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] Concatenated JSON can be converted into line-delimited JSON by a suitable JSON utility such as jq.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] Record separator-delimited JSON streaming allows JSON text sequences to be delimited without the requirement that the JSON formatter exclude whitespace.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] Since JSON text sequences cannot contain control characters, a record separator character can be used to delimit the sequences.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] In addition, it is suggested that each JSON text sequence be followed by a line feed character to allow proper handling of top-level JSON objects that are not self delimiting (numbers, true, false, and null).
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] This format is also known as JSON Text Sequences or MIME type `application/json-seq`, and is formally described in IETF RFC 7464.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] Concatenated JSON streaming allows the sender to simply write each JSON object into the stream with no delimiters.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] It relies on the receiver using a parser that can recognize and *emit* each JSON object as the terminating character is parsed.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] Concatenated JSON isn't a new format, it's simply a name for streaming multiple JSON objects without any delimiters.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] The advantage of this format is that it can handle JSON objects that have been formatted with embedded newline characters, e.g., pretty-printed for human readability.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] Implementations that rely on line-based input may require a newline character after each JSON object in order for the object to be emitted by the parser in a timely manner.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] (Otherwise the line may remain in the input buffer without being passed to the parser.) This is rarely recognised as an issue because terminating JSON objects with a newline character is very common.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] Length-prefixed or framed JSON streaming allows the sender to explicitly state the length of each message.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] It relies on the receiver using a parser that can recognize each length *n* and then read the following *n* bytes to parse as JSON.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] The advantage of this format is that it can speed up parsing due to the fact that the exact length of each message is explicitly stated, rather than forcing the parser to search for delimiters.
[src:jsonlines/json-streaming] Length-prefixed JSON is also well-suited for TCP applications, where a single "message" may be divided into arbitrary chunks, because the prefixed length tells the parser exactly how many bytes to expect before attempting to parse a JSON string.
[src:jsonlines/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:jsonlines/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:jsonlines/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:jsonlines/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:jsonlines/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:jsonlines/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:jsonlines/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:jsonlines/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:jsonlines/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:jsonlines/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:jsonlines/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:jsonlines/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:jsonlines/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:jsonlines/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:jsonlines/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:jsonlines/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:jsonlines/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:jsonlines/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:jsonlines/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:jsonlines/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:jsonlines/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:jsonlines/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:jsonlines/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:jsonlines/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:jsonlines/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:jsonlines/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:jsonlines/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:jsonlines/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:jsonlines/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:jsonlines/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:jsonlines/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:jsonlines/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:jsonlines/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:jsonlines/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:jsonlines/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:jsonlines/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:jsonlines/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:jsonlines/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:jsonlines/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:jsonlines/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:jsonlines/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:jsonlines/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:jsonlines/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:jsonlines/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:jsonlines/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:jsonlines/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:jsonlines/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:jsonlines/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:jsonlines/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:jsonlines/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:jsonlines/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:jsonlines/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:jsonlines/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:jsonlines/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:jsonlines/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:jsonlines/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:jsonlines/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:jsonlines/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:jsonlines/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:jsonlines/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:jsonlines/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:jsonlines/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:jsonlines/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:jsonlines/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:jsonlines/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:jsonlines/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:jsonlines/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:jsonlines/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:jsonlines/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:jsonlines/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:jsonlines/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:jsonlines/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:jsonlines/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:jsonlines/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:jsonlines/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:jsonlines/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:jsonlines/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:jsonlines/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:jsonlines/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:jsonlines/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:jsonlines/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:jsonlines/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:jsonlines/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:jsonlines/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:jsonlines/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:jsonlines/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:jsonlines/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:jsonlines/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:jsonlines/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:jsonlines/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:jsonlines/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:jsonlines/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:jsonlines/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:jsonlines/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:jsonlines/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:jsonlines/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:jsonlines/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:jsonlines/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:jsonlines/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:jsonlines/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:jsonlines/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:jsonlines/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:jsonlines/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] In computing, **logging** is the act of keeping a log of events that occur in a computer system, such as problems, errors or broad information on current operations.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] These events may occur in the operating system or in other software.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] A message or *log entry* is recorded for each such event.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] These log messages can then be used to monitor and understand the operation of the system, to debug problems, or during an audit.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] Logging is particularly important in multi-user software, to have a central overview of the operation of the system.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] In the simplest case, messages are written to a file, called a *log file*.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] Alternatively, the messages may be written to a dedicated logging system or to a log management software, where it is stored in a database or on a different computer system.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] Specifically, a *transaction log* is a log of the communications between a system and the users of that system, or a data collection method that automatically captures the type, content, or time of transactions made by a person from a terminal with that system.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] For Web searching, a transaction log is an electronic record of interactions that have occurred during a searching episode between a Web search engine and users searching for information on that Web search engine.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] Many operating systems, software frameworks and programs include a logging system.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] A widely used logging standard is Syslog, defined in IETF RFC 5424.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] The Syslog standard enables a dedicated, standardized subsystem to generate, filter, record, and analyze log messages.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] This relieves software developers of having to design and code their ad hoc logging systems.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] It can also be useful to combine log file entries from multiple sources.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] It is a different combination that may yield between with related events on different servers.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] Other solutions employ network-wide querying and reporting.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] Most database systems maintain some kind of *transaction log*, which are not mainly intended as an audit trail for later analysis, and are not intended to be human-readable.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] These logs record changes to the stored data to allow the database to recover from crashes or other data errors and maintain the stored data in a consistent state.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] Thus, database systems usually have both general event logs and transaction logs.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] The use of data stored in transaction logs of Web search engines, Intranets, and websites can provide valuable insight into understanding the information-searching process of online searchers.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] This understanding can enlighten information system design, interface development, and devising the information architecture for content collections.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] Message logs are almost universally plain text files, but IM and VoIP clients (which support textual chat, e.g.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] Skype) might save them in HTML files or in a custom format to ease reading or enable encryption.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] Instant messaging and VoIP clients often offer the chance to store encrypted logs to enhance the user's privacy.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] These logs require a password to be decrypted and viewed, and they are often handled by their respective writing application.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] Some privacy focused messaging services, such as Signal, record minimal logs about users, limiting their information to connection times.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] A *server log* is a log file (or several files) automatically created and maintained by a server consisting of a list of activities it performed.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] A typical example is a web server log which maintains a history of page requests.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] The W3C maintains a standard format (the Common Log Format) for web server log files, but other proprietary formats exist.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] Some servers can log information to computer readable formats (such as JSON) versus the human readable standard.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] More recent entries are typically appended to the end of the file.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] Information about the request, including client IP address, request date/time, page requested, HTTP code, bytes served, user agent, and referrer are typically added.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] This data can be combined into a single file, or separated into distinct logs, such as an access log, error log, or referrer log.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] However, server logs typically do not collect user-specific information.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] These files are usually not accessible to general Internet users, only to the webmaster or other administrative person of an Internet service.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] A statistical analysis of the server log may be used to examine traffic patterns by time of day, day of week, referrer, or user agent.
[src:jsonlines/log-file] Efficient web site administration, adequate hosting resources and the fine tuning of sales efforts can be aided by analysis of the web server logs.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] In computer science, a **record** (also called a **structure**, **struct**, **user-defined type (UDT)**, or **compound data type**) is a composite data structure – a collection of fields, possibly of different data types, typically fixed in number and sequence.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] For example, a date could be stored as a record containing a numeric *year* field, a *month* field represented as a string, and a numeric *day-of-month* field.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] A circle record might contain a numeric *radius* and a *center* that is a *point* record containing *x* and *y* coordinates.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Notable applications include the programming language *record type* and for row-based storage, data organized as a sequence of records, such as a database table, spreadsheet or comma-separated values (CSV) file.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] In general, a record type value is stored in memory and row-based storage is in mass storage.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] A *record type* is a data type that describes such values and variables.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Most modern programming languages allow the programmer to define new record types.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] The definition includes specifying the data type of each field and an identifier (name or label) by which it can be accessed.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] In type theory, product types (with no field names) are generally preferred due to their simplicity, but proper record types are studied in languages such as System F-sub.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Since type-theoretical records may contain first-class function-typed fields in addition to data, they can express many features of object-oriented programming.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] In the context of storage such as in a database or spreadsheet a record is often called a *row* and each field is called a column.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] In object-oriented programming, an object is a record that contains state and method fields.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] A record is similar to a mathematical tuple, although a tuple may or may not be considered a record, and vice versa, depending on conventions and the programming language.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] In the same vein, a record type can be viewed as the computer language analog of the Cartesian product of two or more mathematical sets, or the implementation of an abstract product type in a specific language.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] A record differs from an array in that a record's elements (fields) are determined by the definition of the record, and may be heterogeneous whereas an array is a collection of elements with the same type.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] The parameters of a function can be viewed collectively as the fields of a record and passing arguments to the function can be viewed as assigning the input parameters to the record fields.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] At a low-level, a function call includes an *activation record* or *call frame*, that contains the parameters as well as other fields such as local variables and the return address.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] The concept of a record can be traced to various types of tables and ledgers used in accounting since remote times.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] The modern notion of records in computer science, with fields of well-defined type and size, was already implicit in 19th century mechanical calculators, such as Babbage's Analytical Engine.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] The original machine-readable medium used for data (as opposed to control) was the punch card used for records in the 1890 United States census: each punch card was a single record.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Compare the journal entry from 1880 and the punch card from 1895.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Records were well-established in the first half of the 20th century, when most data processing was done using punched cards.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Typically, each record of a data file would be recorded on one punched card, with specific columns assigned to specific fields.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Generally, a record was the smallest unit that could be read from external storage (e.g., card reader, tape, or disk).
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] The contents of punchcard-style records were originally called "unit records" because punchcards had pre-determined document lengths.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] When storage systems became more advanced with the use of hard drives and magnetic tape, variable-length records became the standard.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] A variable-length record is a record in which the size of the record in bytes is approximately equal to the sum of the sizes of its fields.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] This was not possible to do before more advanced storage hardware was invented because all of the punchcards had to conform to pre-determined document lengths that the computer could read, since at the time the cards had to be physically fed into a machine.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Most machine language implementations and early assembly languages did not have special syntax for records, but the concept was available (and extensively used) through the use of index registers, indirect addressing, and self-modifying code.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Some early computers, such as the IBM 1620, had hardware support for delimiting records and fields, and special instructions for copying such records.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] The concept of records and fields was central in some early file sorting and tabulating utilities, such as IBM's Report Program Generator (RPG).
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] COBOL was the first widespread programming language to support record types, and its record definition facilities were quite sophisticated at the time.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] The language allows for the definition of nested records with alphanumeric, integer, and fractional fields of arbitrary size and precision, and fields that automatically format any value assigned to them (e.g., insertion of currency signs, decimal points, and digit group separators).
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Each file is associated with a record variable where data is read into or written from.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] COBOL also provides a `MOVE` `CORRESPONDING` statement that assigns corresponding fields of two records according to their names.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] The early languages developed for numeric computing, such as FORTRAN (up to FORTRAN IV) and ALGOL 60, did not support record types; but later versions of those languages, such as FORTRAN 77 and ALGOL 68 did add them.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] The original Lisp programming language too was lacking records (except for the built-in cons cell), but its S-expressions provided an adequate surrogate.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] The Pascal programming language was one of the first languages to fully integrate record types with other basic types into a logically consistent type system.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] The PL/I language provided for COBOL-style records.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] The C language provides the record concept using structs.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Most languages designed after Pascal (such as Ada, Modula, and Java), also supported records.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Java introduced records in Java 17 and C# introduced records in C#.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Records were introduced to Java to simplify data aggregate classes with less boilerplate, making all fields `final` and `private`, automatically generating all-argument constructors, getters, and the methods `boolean equals()`, `int hashCode()`, and `String toString()`.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Java records all implicitly extend `java.lang.Record`.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Although records are not often used in their original context anymore (i.e. being used solely for the purpose of containing data), records influenced newer object-oriented programming languages and relational database management systems.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Since records provided more modularity in the way data was stored and handled, they are better suited at representing complex, real-world concepts than the primitive data types provided by default in languages.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] This influenced later languages such as C++, Python, JavaScript, and Objective-C which address the same modularity needs of programming.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Objects in these languages are essentially records with the addition of methods and inheritance, which allow programmers to manipulate the way data behaves instead of only the contents of a record.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Many programmers regard records as obsolete now since object-oriented languages have features that far surpass what records are capable of.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] On the other hand, many programmers argue that the low overhead and ability to use records in assembly language make records still relevant when programming with low levels of abstraction.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Today, the most popular languages on the TIOBE index, an indicator of the popularity of programming languages, have been influenced in some way by records due to the fact that they are object oriented.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Query languages such as SQL and Object Query Language were also influenced by the concept of records.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] These languages allow the programmer to store sets of data, which are essentially records, in tables.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] This data can then be retrieved using a primary key.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] The tables themselves are also records which may have a foreign key: a key that references data in another table.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Some languages provide facilities that enumerate the fields of a record.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] This facility is needed to implement certain services such as debugging, garbage collection, and serialization.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] It requires some degree of type polymorphism.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] In contexts that support record subtyping, operations include adding and removing fields of a record.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] A specific record type implies that a specific set of fields are present, but values of that type may contain additional fields.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] A record with fields *x*, *y*, and *z* would thus belong to the type of records with fields *x* and *y*, as would a record with fields *x*, *y*, and *r*.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] The rationale is that passing an (*x*,*y*,*z*) record to a function that expects an (*x*,*y*) record as argument should work, since that function will find all the fields it requires within the record.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Many ways of practically implementing records in programming languages would have trouble with allowing such variability, but the matter is a central characteristic of record types in more theoretical contexts.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Most languages allow assignment between records that have exactly the same record type (including same field types and names, in the same order).
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Depending on the language, however, two record data types defined separately may be regarded as distinct types even if they have exactly the same fields.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] In this alternative, the two operands are still required to have the same sequence of field types.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Some languages may also require that corresponding types have the same size and encoding as well, so that the whole record can be assigned as an uninterpreted bit string.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Other languages may be more flexible in this regard, and require only that each value field can be legally assigned to the corresponding variable field; so that, for example, a short integer field can be assigned to a long integer field, or vice versa.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Other languages (such as COBOL) may match fields and values by their names, rather than positions.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] These same possibilities apply to the comparison of two record values for equality.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Some languages may also allow order comparisons ('<'and '>'), using the lexicographic order based on the comparison of individual fields.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] PL/I allows both of the preceding types of assignment, and also allows *structure expressions*, such as `a = a+1;` where "a" is a record, or structure in PL/I terminology.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] In Algol 68, if `Pts` was an array of records, each with integer fields `X` and `Y`, one could write `Y **of** Pts` to obtain an array of integers, consisting of the `Y` fields of all the elements of `Pts`.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] As a result, the statements `Y **of** Pts[3] := 7` and `(Y **of** Pts)[3] := 7` would have the same effect.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] In Pascal, the command `with R do S` would execute the command sequence `S` as if all the fields of record `R` had been declared as variables.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Similarly to entering a different namespace in an object-oriented language like C#, it is no longer necessary to use the record name as a prefix to access the fields.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] So, instead of writing `Pt.X := 5; Pt.Y := Pt.X + 3` one could write `with Pt do begin X := 5; Y := X + 3 end`.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] The representation of a record in memory varies depending on the programming language.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Often, fields are stored in consecutive memory locations, in the same order as they are declared in the record type.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] This may result in two or more fields stored into the same word of memory; indeed, this feature is often used in systems programming to access specific bits of a word.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] On the other hand, most compilers will add padding fields, mostly invisible to the programmer, in order to comply with alignment constraints imposed by the machine—say, that a floating point field must occupy a single word.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Some languages may implement a record as an array of addresses pointing to the fields (and, possibly, to their names and/or types).
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Objects in object-oriented languages are often implemented in rather complicated ways, especially in languages that allow multiple class inheritance.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] A *self-defining record* is a type of record which contains information to identify the record type and to locate information within the record.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] It may contain the offsets of elements; the elements can therefore be stored in any order or may be omitted.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] The information stored in a self-defining record can be interpreted as metadata for the record, which is similar to what one would expect to find in the UNIX metadata regarding a file, containing information such as the record's creation time and the size of the record in bytes.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Alternatively, various elements of the record, each including an element identifier, can simply follow one another in any order.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] A record, especially in the context of row-based storage, may include **key** fields that allow indexing the records of a collection.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] A primary key is unique throughout all stored records; only one of this key exists.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] In other words, no duplicate may exist for any primary key.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] For example, an employee file might contain employee number, name, department, and salary.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] The employee number will be unique in the organization and will be the primary key.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Depending on the storage medium and file organization, the employee number might be *indexed*—that is also stored in a separate file to make the lookup faster.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] The department code is not necessarily unique; it may also be indexed, in which case it would be considered a *secondary key*, or *alternate key*.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] If it is not indexed, the entire employee file would have to be scanned to produce a listing of all employees in a specific department.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] Keys are usually chosen in a way that minimizes the chances of multiple values being feasibly mapped to by one key.
[src:jsonlines/record-computer-science] For example, the salary field would not normally be considered usable as a key since many employees will likely have the same salary.
